"""
MKT Christ Commentary — Ezekiel chapters 26–28
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-ezekiel-26-28.py

These three chapters contain the most theologically concentrated Christological
material in the Tyre oracle section.

Key interpretive decisions:
- Ch28 vv12-19 (king of Tyre lament): treated as having a secondary referent beyond
  the historical king — the description of a being in Eden, blameless from creation,
  anointed cherub guardian, who fell through pride, matches no historical king and has been
  read as depicting the spiritual power behind Tyre (cf. Isa 14:12-15 for Babylon's king).
  The Christological angle is Christ as the one who retains the perfection the guardian
  cherub lost and who restores access to Eden (cf. Heb 12:22; Rev 2:7).
- Ch27 merchant catalog (vv12-24): treated as background for Rev 18's Babylon lament;
  the commercial empire judged anticipates Christ's final judgment on worldly economic systems
- Ch26 vv15-18: the mourning of sea-kings directly parallels Rev 18:9 — treated as
  the OT source for the NT eschatological judgment-of-commercial-Babylon motif
- Ch28 v24 "brier and thorn removed": read in light of Gen 3:18 curse (thorns); Christ
  absorbing the curse-of-thorns at the crucifixion as the removal of the brier-and-thorn
  that the surrounding nations represented
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

EZEKIEL_CHRIST = {
  "26": {
    "1": "<p>The date header establishes that this oracle against Tyre was delivered in the same period as the fall of Jerusalem (the eleventh year, though the month is missing in the Hebrew — possibly a scribal gap). The historical coincidence is theologically significant: just as YHWH judges his own covenant city, he also judges the city that gloated over its fall. In Christ, this double-judgment structure is resolved: the cross is both the judgment of Jerusalem's sin (Matt 23:37-38; Luke 19:41-44) and the defeat of the world's proud systems (John 12:31: &#8220;now the ruler of this world will be cast out&#8221;).</p>",
    "2": "<p>Tyre's sin is gloating over Jerusalem's fall: &#8220;Aha! The gate of the peoples is broken; it has swung open to me.&#8221; The commercial city sees Jerusalem's destruction as an opportunity — trade routes through the Levantine corridor would be redirected through Tyre. Christ's parable of the tenants (Matt 21:33-44) echoes this dynamic: those who exploit the owner's absence to seize the inheritance will face the owner's return. Tyre's calculation — Jerusalem's loss is Tyre's gain — mirrors every worldly scheme that profits from the suffering of others. The same logic underlies Edom's treachery (Ezek 25:12; Obad 11-14). Christ's judgment reverses this inversion.</p>",
    "3": "<p>&#8220;Many nations against you as the sea brings up its waves&#8221; — YHWH's judgment on Tyre comes in waves, not a single blow: Nebuchadnezzar's 13-year siege (585-573 BCE), then Alexander's causeway conquest (332 BCE), then subsequent decline through the Hellenistic and Roman periods. This cumulative judgment anticipates the eschatological pattern in Revelation: the judgments come in sequences (seals, trumpets, bowls), each wave deeper than the last. Christ is the one who &#8220;rides on the waves&#8221; (Matt 14:25-26) — he is the Lord of the seas whose waves of judgment no earthly power can withstand.</p>",
    "4": "<p>&#8220;I will also scrape the soil from her and make her a bare rock&#8221; — the stripping of Tyre to bare rock is the judgment of exposure: what lay under the beauty and commerce is simply stone. Alexander the Great literally scraped the mainland rubble of Old Tyre into the sea to build his causeway to the island fortress in 332 BCE, leaving the mainland site bare — one of the most precise fulfillments of prophetic detail in ancient history. Christologically, the cross is the ultimate &#8220;bare rock&#8221; moment: the world's pretensions stripped away, nothing left but the bare truth of divine judgment and grace. Christ himself is the &#8220;rock&#8221; (1 Cor 10:4; Matt 7:24-25) — but it is not bare stone for destruction; it is the foundation of life.</p>",
    "5": "<p>&#8220;She will become a place in the middle of the sea for the spreading of nets&#8221; — the prophetic image is of fishermen using the ruins of the great city as a platform for drying fishing nets. The fishing imagery recalls Jesus's call of the disciples: &#8220;Follow me, and I will make you fishers of men&#8221; (Matt 4:19). Where Tyre spread commercial wealth across the seas, the disciples would spread the gospel net. The contrast is instructive: Tyre's nets caught material goods; the gospel net catches human souls. The place where commercial empire falls becomes the place from which the kingdom of God spreads.</p>",
    "6": "<p>&#8220;Her daughters on the mainland will be slain by the sword, and they shall know that I am the LORD&#8221; — the &#8220;daughters&#8221; are the dependent mainland settlements. The knowledge formula that follows every judgment announces the epistemological outcome: YHWH's identity is disclosed through his acts of judgment. Christ is the ultimate disclosure of YHWH's identity — not through judgment but through the cross and resurrection. The &#8220;they will know that I am the LORD&#8221; formula finds its NT fulfillment in Phil 2:10-11: &#8220;at the name of Jesus every knee shall bow and every tongue confess that Jesus Christ is Lord&#8221; — universal acknowledgment through the revelation of Christ's lordship.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Nebuchadnezzar is described as &#8220;king of kings&#8221; (<em>melek hamelachim</em>) — the supreme title of ANE monarchy, used also for Artaxerxes (Ezra 7:12) and in the NT as Christ's title (Rev 17:14; 19:16: &#8220;King of kings and Lord of lords&#8221;). The use of &#8220;king of kings&#8221; for Nebuchadnezzar, the temporary human instrument of divine judgment, is itself an implicit pointing beyond him: the true King of kings is the one who employs Nebuchadnezzar as his sword. Christ's title &#8220;King of kings&#8221; in Revelation asserts that what Nebuchadnezzar was called by flattery, Christ is by nature.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The detailed siege terminology (siege works, mound, siege engines, shields) describes the literal mechanics of Babylonian military conquest. Christ's conquest is accomplished by entirely opposite means: not with battering rams against walls but with the &#8220;sword of the Spirit, which is the word of God&#8221; (Eph 6:17), not by force but by the power of resurrection life (2 Cor 10:4-5: &#8220;the weapons of our warfare are not carnal but mighty in God for pulling down strongholds&#8221;). The contrast between Nebuchadnezzar's military siege and Christ's gospel conquest is the contrast between the first and last kingdoms.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Battering rams against walls and towers broken down — the progressive dismantling of Tyre's defenses mirrors the progressive revelation that no human security system is permanent. Hebrews 12:26-27 applies the shaking of earthly structures explicitly to Christ's kingdom: &#8220;this phrase, 'Yet once more,' indicates the removing of things that are shaken ... in order that the things that cannot be shaken may remain.&#8221; The walls of Tyre are among the &#8220;shakeable&#8221; things; Christ's kingdom is the &#8220;unshakeable&#8221; one that remains after all earthly powers are leveled.</p>",
    "10": "<p>&#8220;Your walls will shake at the noise of horsemen, wheels, and chariots when he enters your gates&#8221; — the overwhelming military force that causes walls to tremble contrasts with Christ's entry into Jerusalem on a donkey (Matt 21:5: &#8220;your king is coming to you, humble and mounted on a donkey&#8221;, citing Zech 9:9). The King of kings entered the world's great city not with the noise of war-horses but in deliberate humility. Yet this humble entry led to the judgment that Zech 9:9-10 itself anticipated: the dismantling of war-horses and chariots and the proclamation of peace &#8220;to the nations.&#8221;</p>",
    "11": "<p>&#8220;His horses' hooves will trample all your streets; he will slaughter your people with the sword and your strong pillars will collapse to the ground&#8221; — the strong pillars (<em>matsevot oz</em>) were Tyre's commemorative stelae and victory monuments. In Revelation 3:12 Christ promises to make the overcomer &#8220;a pillar in the temple of my God, never to go out of it&#8221; — the pillars that earthly powers erect and YHWH tears down are replaced with human beings incorporated permanently into the divine temple. The judgment of Tyre's pillars clears the way for a different kind of architectural permanence.</p>",
    "12": "<p>&#8220;They will cast your stones, your timber, and your soil into the sea&#8221; — this verse is strikingly fulfilled by Alexander's 332 BCE causeway: he used the ruins of mainland Tyre (stones, timber, and soil) as construction material, dragging them into the sea to build the road to the island city. The historical precision of this prophecy (verified by ancient sources including Arrian's Anabasis) is one of the strongest arguments for the predictive character of biblical prophecy. Christ fulfills prophecy not in hidden, allegorized ways but in sometimes startlingly concrete historical events that vindicate the prophetic claim.</p>",
    "13": "<p>&#8220;I will put an end to the noise of your songs, and the sound of your harps will be heard no more&#8221; — the silencing of Tyre's music is the direct source for Revelation 18:22: &#8220;the sound of harpists and musicians, of flute players and trumpeters, will be heard in you no more.&#8221; In Revelation 18, the fallen &#8220;Babylon&#8221; is a composite of every proud commercial civilization including Tyre. Christ's final judgment silences the music of worldly self-celebration — but it is simultaneously replaced by the &#8220;new song&#8221; of Rev 5:9 and 14:3, the song of the redeemed before the Lamb. One music ends; another begins.</p>",
    "14": "<p>&#8220;You will be a place for the spreading of nets and will never be rebuilt&#8221; — modern Tyre (Sur in Lebanon) does exist as a city, which has led to debate about this verse. The most precise interpretation is that the ancient Tyre known for its commercial glory was permanently ended — the island fortress that Alexander conquered never recovered its previous stature. Christ's fulfillment of Ezekiel's judgment-oracles is not always through direct historical completion but through the principle they embody: no worldly system that opposes God's purposes will ultimately stand. The &#8220;never be rebuilt&#8221; points to the eschatological finality of Christ's judgment (Rev 18:21: &#8220;Babylon the great city will be thrown down with violence and will be found no more&#8221;).</p>",
    "15": "<p>&#8220;Will not the coastlands tremble at the sound of your fall?&#8221; — the international trembling at Tyre's fall is the &#8220;fear of the LORD&#8221; motif made global: when YHWH acts in judgment, the nations recognize his power. Christ's cross and resurrection had the same effect — &#8220;the earth shook and the rocks split ... the centurion ... said, 'Surely he was the Son of God!'&#8221; (Matt 27:51-54). The trembling of the nations at divine action is consistent from Tyre's fall to the crucifixion to the final judgment.</p>",
    "16": "<p>&#8220;All the princes of the sea will descend from their thrones, remove their robes, and strip off their embroidered garments; they will clothe themselves with trembling&#8221; — this mourning gesture of the sea-princes is directly cited in Revelation 18:9-10: &#8220;the kings of the earth who committed immorality and lived in luxury with her, they will weep and wail over her ... standing far off ... saying, 'Alas! Alas! You great city, you mighty city, Babylon!'&#8221; The voluntary demotion of princes (removing robes, sitting on the ground) reflects the shock of seeing that even the mightiest commercial empire can fall. Before Christ's judgment seat, all earthly thrones are equally temporary.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The lament: &#8220;How you are destroyed, you who were inhabited by seafarers — you renowned city, mighty on the sea!&#8221; — the mourning over Tyre anticipates the mourning over Babylon in Rev 18 but also the mourning over Jerusalem that Jesus himself initiated (Matt 23:37-38; Luke 19:41-44). Jesus wept over Jerusalem with the same grief that Ezekiel's sea-princes show over Tyre — but with the additional dimension that he was simultaneously pronouncing and bearing the judgment. The one who laments the fall of the great city is also the one who executes the judgment that causes the fall.</p>",
    "18": "<p>&#8220;Now the coastlands tremble on the day of your fall; the islands in the sea are dismayed at your end&#8221; — the ripple effect of Tyre's judgment across the maritime world. In Christ's first coming, the response to his death and resurrection created exactly this kind of international trembling: from Jerusalem to Judea to Samaria to the ends of the earth (Acts 1:8), the impact of the cross spread outward like waves from the center. The &#8220;islands&#8221; (<em>iyim</em>) of the prophets are often the distant Gentile territories (Isa 41:1; 42:4; 49:1) — the nations at the ends of the earth who will ultimately be brought to the knowledge of YHWH.</p>",
    "19": "<p>&#8220;When I bring up the deep over you and the great waters cover you&#8221; — the primordial waters (<em>tehom</em>) covering Tyre evokes the flood narrative (Gen 7:11: &#8220;all the springs of the great deep burst forth&#8221;) and reverses the creation narrative (the waters were restrained at creation so dry land appeared; here they are released again in un-creation). Christ's death is described in similar de-creation language: darkness covered the land (Matt 27:45; Amos 8:9), the temple curtain tore (Matt 27:51), the earth shook. The judgment of Tyre's un-creation is a type of the new creation that comes through Christ's death and resurrection — the old order passing away to make way for the new.</p>",
    "20": "<p>&#8220;I will bring you down with those who descend to the pit, to the ancient peoples ... but I will set glory in the land of the living&#8221; — this verse contains an extraordinary juxtaposition: while Tyre descends to the pit with the dead, YHWH will &#8220;set glory in the land of the living.&#8221; The glory (<em>tzvi</em>) set in the land of the living while the proud go to the pit is the resurrection-reversal: Christ descends to the realm of the dead (1 Pet 3:19; Acts 2:27 citing Ps 16:10: &#8220;you will not abandon my soul to Sheol&#8221;) but is set in glory — the land of the living — through the resurrection. The contrast between Tyre's permanent descent and the glory established in the land of the living is ultimately the contrast between death and resurrection.</p>",
    "21": "<p>&#8220;You will be no more. Though you are sought, you will never be found again&#8221; — the permanent disappearance of Tyre from the stage of history finds its eschatological completion in Revelation 18:21: &#8220;Babylon the great city will be thrown down with violence and will be found no more forever.&#8221; In Christ, the &#8220;will never be found again&#8221; verdict applies to every power that opposes God: &#8220;the last enemy to be destroyed is death&#8221; (1 Cor 15:26); &#8220;and the devil who had deceived them was thrown into the lake of fire&#8221; (Rev 20:10). What YHWH declared about Tyre is the template for the final verdict on every force of pride and opposition.</p>"
  },
  "27": {
    "1": "<p>The introduction to the lament over Tyre as a ship is a simple date-and-call formula — but the form matters. The lament (<em>qinah</em>) is the dirge-form, the song of the dead. Ezekiel sings the death-song over Tyre before it has happened — the prophetic perfect. Christ employs the same prophetic mourning in Luke 19:41-44, weeping over Jerusalem before its destruction and describing its fate in prophetic past tense. The prophet who sings the dirge over the living city is like Christ who announces the coming judgment while simultaneously grieving it.</p>",
    "2": "<p>&#8220;Raise a lamentation over Tyre&#8221; — the call to lamentation places the prophet in the role of mourner-on-behalf-of-the-doomed. Ezekiel does not celebrate Tyre's fall but grieves it. This is the prophetic pathos that Heschel identified as the distinctive mark of Israelite prophecy: the prophet shares YHWH's grief over the necessity of judgment. Christ embodies this pathos most fully: he is simultaneously the judge who pronounces the verdict and the one who weeps over those condemned (John 11:35; Luke 19:41-44). The God who judges is the God who mourns.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Tyre's self-assessment: &#8220;I am perfect in beauty&#8221; (<em>ani kelilat yofi</em>) — the same claim Ezekiel directs ironically against Jerusalem in 16:14 (&#8220;your beauty was perfect through my splendor that I had bestowed on you&#8221;). Tyre claims inherent beauty; Jerusalem's beauty was derived. Christ alone is inherently &#8220;perfect in beauty&#8221; — Ps 45:2: &#8220;you are the most handsome of the sons of men; grace is poured upon your lips.&#8221; The beauty that Tyre claimed for itself and Jerusalem received as a gift is actually Christ's own — the beautiful one from whom all creaturely beauty derives.</p>",
    "4": "<p>&#8220;Your builders have perfected your beauty&#8221; — Tyre's beauty was constructed, engineered, designed. The builders who perfected the ship's beauty are human craftsmen. Christ's beauty, by contrast, is uncreated: he is the &#8220;radiance of the glory of God and the exact imprint of his nature&#8221; (Heb 1:3) — not constructed but eternally generated. The ship's beauty will eventually be wrecked (v.26); the beauty of the incarnate Son is permanent and the foundation of the new creation's glory (Rev 21:11).</p>",
    "5": "<p>The ship's planks from Senir (the Amorite name for Hermon, Deut 3:9) and the mast from Lebanon cedars — the finest available timber. The cedar of Lebanon was the premier building material for temples (1 Kings 5:6-10), including Solomon's temple. Christ is the true temple (John 2:19-21) — the place where YHWH dwells — and the cedars that Tyre used for commerce, Solomon used for worship, and Ezekiel uses as an image of Assyrian imperial pride (ch.31), are the raw material of that which points to the divine dwelling in human flesh.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Oaks of Bashan and Cyprus ivory for the deck — the best materials from the east and west. The Bashan oaks were famous for their strength (Isa 2:13; Zech 11:2); Bashan is also associated with the Rephaim/giants and is a biblical symbol of formidable earthly strength. In Christ's kingship, he who &#8220;descended to the lower parts of the earth&#8221; (Eph 4:9 — to the realm where the Bashan-strength had no power over the dead) is the true master of all materials and domains.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Egyptian linen for the sail, purple and blue from Elishah (possibly Cyprus or the Aegean) for the awning — the finest luxury textiles. The purple and blue were the colors of the tabernacle curtains (Exod 26:1) and the high-priestly garments (Exod 28:4-6). Christ was clothed in purple by the soldiers in mockery (John 19:2) — unknowingly robing the High Priest in the colors of the sanctuary. The purple that commercial Tyre used for beauty, the tabernacle used for holiness, and the soldiers used for mockery, becomes in Revelation 19:13-16 the robe of Christ the conquering King.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Sidon and Arvad as oarsmen — skilled Phoenician sailors directing the ship. The skilled navigation of Tyre's commercial enterprise draws on the whole Phoenician maritime tradition. Christ calls fishermen (Matt 4:18-22) — not navigators of commerce but workers in the ancient subsistence economy — to be &#8220;fishers of men.&#8221; The contrast between Tyre's commercial pilots and Christ's fishing-disciples is the contrast between the economy of acquisition and the economy of grace.</p>",
    "9": "<p>&#8220;All the ships of the sea with their sailors were in you to trade your merchandise&#8221; — the universal commerce flowing to Tyre. In Christ, the nations flow not to a commercial hub but to a person: John 12:32: &#8220;I, when I am lifted up from the earth, will draw all people to myself.&#8221; The attraction of the cross replaces the attraction of the market — and the &#8220;all&#8221; who are drawn to Christ exceeds the &#8220;all the ships&#8221; that traded at Tyre.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Persian, Lydian, and Libyan soldiers in Tyre's army — a multiethnic mercenary force. The military power that Tyre's wealth could buy was formidable. Christ's army in Revelation 19:14 is &#8220;the armies of heaven, wearing fine linen, white and clean&#8221; — not mercenaries bought with commercial wealth but the redeemed clothed in Christ's righteousness. The contrast between Tyre's bought soldiers and Christ's redeemed army is the difference between a commercial transaction and a covenant relationship.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Arvad soldiers on the walls, Gammadim in the towers — military perfection, shields covering every surface, beauty made perfect through armament. Christ's armor is described in Eph 6:10-17, but it is fundamentally different: not bronze shields on a commercial ship's walls but the armor of truth, righteousness, peace, faith, and salvation. The defense of Tyre was its military hardware; the defense of Christ's people is his character and work applied to them.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Tarshish trading silver, iron, tin, and lead — the metals of ancient commerce. Tarshish is associated with the far west (possibly Spain or Sardinia) and represents the farthest reaches of the known trading world. The metals of Tarshish are raw materials for industry and weapons. In Christ, the metals are transformed: the &#8220;silver&#8221; of redemption (1 Pet 1:18: &#8220;you were ransomed ... not with perishable things such as silver or gold, but with the precious blood of Christ&#8221;) exceeds all commercial metals. The ransoming of humanity cost more than Tyre's entire treasury.</p>",
    "13": "<p>&#8220;They traded human beings and vessels of bronze in your markets&#8221; — Meshech and Tubal in slave trade and bronze. The commodification of human beings in the ancient commercial system is explicitly named. Christ's redemption is the direct reversal of the slave trade: he purchased people &#8220;for God from every tribe and language and people and nation&#8221; (Rev 5:9) — but not to own them as slaves but to make them &#8220;a kingdom and priests to our God.&#8221; The commerce that traded humans as commodities is overthrown by the One who paid for humans to be liberated into royal priesthood.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Beth-togarmah with horses, war horses, and mules — the cavalry-trade from Armenia (Togarmah = Armenia in later tradition). The horses of war supplied by Togarmah represent military power purchasable through commerce. Christ enters Jerusalem on a humble donkey (Matt 21:5; Zech 9:9), deliberately contrasting his arrival with the war-horse economy. The King who comes to Tyre is bought with Togarmah's war horses; the King who comes to Zion comes in humility. Revelation 19:11 reverses this: Christ comes on a white horse — but the horse is not purchased through commerce; it is the mount of divine judgment.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Dedan and the coastlands with ivory and ebony — luxury goods from Arabia and Africa. The ivory and ebony represent the exotic beauty that wealth could procure from the ends of the earth. The Magi who came to the infant Jesus brought &#8220;gold and frankincense and myrrh&#8221; (Matt 2:11) — luxury goods from the east, echoing the tribute of the nations flowing to Zion that Isaiah envisioned (Isa 60:5-6). What flowed to Tyre as commercial profit flows to Christ as worship: the wealth of the nations becomes the offering of the nations.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Syria with emeralds, purple, embroidered cloth, fine linen, coral, and rubies — the luxury goods of the Levantine trade. These are the same materials used in the tabernacle and priestly vestments: purple, embroidered cloth, and fine linen are the vocabulary of the sanctuary. Everything Tyre used for commercial display, the tabernacle used for divine service. Christ is the fulfillment of the tabernacle-pattern (John 1:14: &#8220;the Word became flesh and tabernacled among us&#8221;) — the sanctuary-materials that commercial empire appropriated are restored to their proper function as the dwelling-place of divine glory.</p>",
    "17": "<p>&#8220;Judah and the land of Israel were your traders; they traded wheat from Minnith, cakes, honey, olive oil, and balm&#8221; — Israel among Tyre's trading partners, supplying agricultural products. The covenant people are embedded in the commercial system of the nations. This is the diagnosis that the prophets repeatedly make: Israel's sin is not only idolatry but the commercialization of covenant life. Christ's cleansing of the temple (John 2:16: &#8220;Stop making my Father's house a house of trade&#8221;) is the definitive purification of the covenant community from Tyre's commercial spirit.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Damascus with wine and wool — the agricultural luxury products of Syria. The extensive merchant catalog (vv.12-24) is the OT's most detailed picture of ancient international commerce, mapping the trading world from Spain to India. It is the direct source for Rev 18's Babylon-lament catalog (vv.12-13) which lists 28 categories of luxury goods. The point of both catalogs is the same: all the world's material wealth, assembled and organized by human commercial genius, will be swept away in a moment. Only what Christ builds — his church (Matt 16:18) — will stand.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Dan and Javan (Greece) from Uzal with wrought iron, cassia, and fragrant calamus — iron for tools and weapons, spices for luxury use. The cassia and calamus are ingredients in the holy anointing oil of the tabernacle (Exod 30:23-25). The spices that flowed through Tyre's markets for commercial purchase were also the sacred ingredients of covenant worship. Christ's anointing with costly nard (Mark 14:3-9) is the NT equivalent: &#8220;wherever the gospel is proclaimed in the whole world, what she has done will be told in memory of her.&#8221; The commercial spice-trade is transformed into an act of devotion.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Dedan with saddlecloths for riding — equipment for horses and camels, the transportation infrastructure of ancient trade. The saddlecloths represent the practical underside of luxury commerce: the logistics, the animals, the equipment. Christ entered Jerusalem on a borrowed donkey with cloaks spread on the road (Matt 21:7-8) — the simplest possible version of royal transportation. The king who owned all the saddlecloths of Dedan came to his city in the humility that the commercial mind cannot recognize as royal.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Arabia and Kedar with lambs, rams, and goats — the pastoral economy of the desert peoples. The lambs and rams connect to the sacrificial system: Kedar's flocks supplied both commerce and, potentially, temple sacrifices. Christ is &#8220;the Lamb of God who takes away the sin of the world&#8221; (John 1:29) — the One to whom all the lambs of commercial and sacrificial trade ultimately pointed. The lambs traded through Tyre's markets were commercial commodities; the Lamb of God is the one whose sacrifice ends all commercial and sacrificial transactions.</p>",
    "22": "<p>&#8220;The merchants of Sheba and Raamah traded with you; they traded in the finest of all spices, all kinds of precious stones, and gold&#8221; — Sheba (southern Arabia / Ethiopia) with spices, precious stones, and gold echoes the Queen of Sheba's tribute to Solomon (1 Kings 10:2, 10: &#8220;she gave the king 120 talents of gold, large quantities of spices, and precious stones&#8221;) and anticipates the Magi's gifts to the infant Jesus (Matt 2:11: &#8220;they presented gifts of gold and frankincense and myrrh&#8221;). The wealth of nations flowing to YHWH's anointed king is a recurring pattern: Tyre monetizes it for commerce; Jesus receives it as eschatological tribute.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Haran, Canneh, Eden, Asshur, Chilmad — trade partners from Mesopotamia and northern Syria. The geographic extent of Tyre's trading network spans from Spain (Tarshish, v.12) to India (possibly Dedan's eastern connections) and from north Africa to Mesopotamia. This global commerce is the pre-modern world's version of what Paul describes as the principalities and powers ruling through &#8220;the elementary principles of the world&#8221; (Gal 4:3; Col 2:8): the organized systems of human commerce that bind people to the material world. Christ's liberation from these systems (Col 2:15: &#8220;disarming the rulers and authorities ... triumphing over them in the cross&#8221;) is the defeat of the commercial empire behind every Tyre.</p>",
    "24": "<p>&#8220;Choice garments, in blue and embroidered cloth, in chests of fine clothing bound with cords&#8221; — the luxury clothing trade. Clothing in the OT carries theological weight: the garments of Adam and Eve (Gen 3:21, YHWH provides clothing after the fall), the high-priestly garments (Exod 28), the robe of righteousness (Isa 61:10), the filthy garments of Joshua the high priest (Zech 3:3-5). Christ's seamless tunic (John 19:23-24, soldiers cast lots for it citing Ps 22:18) is the NT clothing-symbol: the garment that cannot be divided, the covering that surpasses all Tyre's blue and embroidered robes.</p>",
    "25": "<p>&#8220;The ships of Tarshish carried your merchandise; you were filled and made very glorious in the heart of the seas&#8221; — Tyre at its peak: &#8220;filled and very glorious.&#8221; The glory of the commercial empire at its apex is the prelude to its destruction (v.26). The pattern of &#8220;fullness leading to fall&#8221; is the prophetic diagnosis of Tyre, Assyria, Babylon, and ultimately of every self-sufficient civilization. Christ's fullness (<em>pleroma</em>) is the opposite: &#8220;in him the whole fullness of deity dwells bodily&#8221; (Col 2:9) — not the fullness of accumulated commercial wealth but the fullness of divine being, which cannot be wrecked by any east wind.</p>",
    "26": "<p>&#8220;The east wind has wrecked you in the heart of the seas&#8221; — the east wind is YHWH's instrument of judgment throughout the OT: the east wind dried up the Red Sea (Exod 14:21), brought the plague of locusts (Exod 10:13), destroyed Jonah's shade (Jon 4:8), and scattered Israel (Ps 48:7). Tyre's merchant ship is wrecked by the same wind that YHWH wields in covenant judgment. Christ, who &#8220;rebuked the wind and the raging waves&#8221; (Luke 8:24), is the master of the east wind that wrecks Tyre — the same power that judges is the power that stills the storm for his people.</p>",
    "27": "<p>&#8220;All will sink into the heart of the seas on the day of your ruin&#8221; — the totality of the sinking is emphasized: wealth, merchandise, goods, mariners, pilots, caulkers, dealers, soldiers — everything. The all-encompassing loss echoes the rich man in Luke 12:20: &#8220;You fool! This night your soul is required of you, and the things you have prepared, whose will they be?&#8221; The day of ruin comes suddenly, and nothing of the commercial structure survives. Only what is built on Christ — &#8220;a stone of testing, a precious cornerstone, a sure foundation&#8221; (Isa 28:16) — survives the wreck.</p>",
    "28": "<p>&#8220;At the sound of the cry of your pilots the countryside shakes&#8221; — the lament of the skilled navigators causes the land itself to tremble. The &#8220;shaking of the earth&#8221; motif in prophetic texts is regularly associated with divine judgment and theophany (Isa 2:21; 13:13; Hag 2:6-7; Heb 12:26-27). The cry of Tyre's pilots — the most skilled, the highest-paid, the most celebrated — signals the collapse of human expertise before the divine judgment. &#8220;I will destroy the wisdom of the wise, and the discernment of the discerning I will thwart&#8221; (1 Cor 1:19, citing Isa 29:14) — Christ crucified is &#8220;foolishness to Greeks&#8221; (1 Cor 1:23), the cosmic rebuke of all human navigational skill.</p>",
    "29": "<p>&#8220;All who handle the oar — the mariners and all the pilots of the sea — will come down from their ships and stand on the shore&#8221; — the maritime community's abandonment of their vessels in mourning for Tyre. They stand on solid ground having left the sea — the instability of the commercial enterprise becomes apparent only in the moment of catastrophic loss. Christ invites his disciples to come down from their boats: Peter walks on the water (Matt 14:29-30), then sinks, then is caught by Christ. The invitation to leave the commercial sea and stand on solid ground is the gospel's call.</p>",
    "30": "<p>&#8220;They will raise their voices over you and cry out bitterly; they will throw dust on their heads and roll in ashes&#8221; — the mourning rituals of the ancient world: dust on the head, rolling in ashes. These are the gestures of the deepest grief (Job 2:12-13; Lam 3:29; Josh 7:6). The mourning that the nations perform over Tyre is a parody of genuine repentance: they grieve the loss of their commercial partner, not their sin. Christ's call is to genuine mourning over sin (Matt 5:4: &#8220;blessed are those who mourn, for they shall be comforted&#8221;) — the sorrow that leads to repentance, not merely the grief of material loss.</p>",
    "31": "<p>Shaved heads and sackcloth for Tyre — the mourning rituals that in the prophets belong to genuine lament for sin (Joel 1:13; Isa 22:12). The merchants perform the form of mourning without the substance. Christ's beatitude (Matt 5:4) and Paul's distinction (2 Cor 7:10: &#8220;godly grief produces repentance leading to salvation, but worldly grief produces death&#8221;) draws exactly this line: the grief over Tyre's fall is worldly grief, producing nothing but despair. The grief over one's sin before Christ is godly grief, producing repentance and life.</p>",
    "32": "<p>&#8220;Who was ever destroyed like Tyre, like one silenced in the midst of the sea?&#8221; — the rhetorical question of Tyre's uniqueness. The same question was asked of Babylon in Jer 50:23 (&#8220;how the hammer of the whole earth has been cut down and broken!&#8221;) and Rev 18:18 (&#8220;What city was like the great city?&#8221;). The lament over unprecedented destruction is itself a theological claim: YHWH's judgment is uniquely comprehensive, not like ordinary military defeat. Christ's cross is also unprecedented: &#8220;Has it ever happened in all your days or in the days of your fathers? Tell your children about it, and let your children tell their children&#8221; (Joel 1:2-3) — the singular, unrepeatable event at the center of history.</p>",
    "33": "<p>&#8220;When your merchandise went out over the seas, you satisfied many peoples; with your great wealth and goods you enriched the kings of the earth&#8221; — Tyre's positive contribution to the ancient world is acknowledged: it genuinely satisfied and enriched. This is not merely hypocritical praise; Tyre's commercial network did create real prosperity for many. The judgment is not that commercial activity is evil but that Tyre claimed ultimate credit and status for what YHWH provided. Christ satisfies far more comprehensively than Tyre: &#8220;I am the bread of life; whoever comes to me shall not hunger, and whoever believes in me shall never thirst&#8221; (John 6:35) — the satisfaction that Tyre's trade offered temporarily, Christ offers permanently.</p>",
    "34": "<p>&#8220;Now you are wrecked by the seas, in the depths of the waters; your merchandise and all your company have sunk with you&#8221; — the wrecking is complete. The &#8220;depths of the waters&#8221; (<em>maamaqqim mayim</em>) recalls Ps 69:2 (&#8220;I have come into deep waters, and the flood sweeps over me&#8221;), the lament of the righteous sufferer — whose words Christ quotes from the cross (Ps 69:21 in John 19:28-29). The depths that swallow Tyre are the same depths that Christ entered in his Passion — but from the depths Christ rose, and from those depths he raises his people (Ps 130:1: &#8220;Out of the depths I cry to you, O LORD&#8221;).</p>",
    "35": "<p>&#8220;All the inhabitants of the coastlands are appalled at you; their kings shudder with horror and their faces are convulsed with fear&#8221; — the face-convulsion of the kings at Tyre's fall echoes the suffering servant's effect: &#8220;so his appearance was marred beyond human semblance, and his form beyond that of the children of mankind — so shall he sprinkle many nations; kings shall shut their mouths because of him&#8221; (Isa 52:14-15). The horror that Tyre's fall produces in kings is matched by the awestruck silence that the servant's suffering and exaltation produces. Both the fall of commercial empire and the exaltation of the suffering servant silence kings.</p>",
    "36": "<p>&#8220;The merchants among the peoples hiss at you; you have come to a horrible end and will be no more forever&#8221; — the merchants' hissing (<em>sharak</em>, a gesture of contemptuous horror) at Tyre's fall is echoed in Lam 2:15 (&#8220;all who pass your way hiss and wag their heads at the daughter of Jerusalem&#8221;) and in the crowd at the crucifixion (Matt 27:39: &#8220;those who passed by derided him, wagging their heads&#8221;). The same contemptuous gesture that the merchants direct at fallen Tyre was directed at Christ on the cross. What looks like the hissing at ultimate failure is, in Christ, the moment of ultimate victory — the moment when the world's contempt meets its match in the Father's vindication through resurrection.</p>"
  },
  "28": {
    "1": "<p>The word-of-the-LORD formula introduces the first Tyre oracle of this chapter, addressed to the prince (<em>nasi</em>) of Tyre. The distinction between prince (<em>nasi</em>, vv.1-10) and king (<em>melek</em>, vv.11-19) is significant: the prince-oracle addresses the historical ruler (probably Ethbaal III, who ruled during Nebuchadnezzar's siege); the king-oracle employs a more elevated register that exceeds the historical ruler. Christ is both the antitype of the pride condemned in vv.1-10 and the fulfillment of the perfection described and lost in vv.12-19.</p>",
    "2": "<p>&#8220;Because your heart is proud and you have said, 'I am a god'&#8221; — the primal sin of hubris: claiming divine status. This is the sin of Adam (Gen 3:5: &#8220;you will be like God&#8221;), of the builders of Babel (Gen 11:4), of Pharaoh (Exod 5:2: &#8220;Who is the LORD that I should obey him?&#8221;), and will be the sin of the man of lawlessness (2 Thess 2:4: &#8220;who opposes and exalts himself against every so-called god or object of worship, so that he takes his seat in the temple of God, proclaiming himself to be God&#8221;). Christ, who truly is God, &#8220;did not count equality with God a thing to be grasped&#8221; (Phil 2:6) — the exact reversal of the Tyre-prince's sin: the human who claimed to be God vs. the God who became human.</p>",
    "3": "<p>&#8220;Behold, you are wiser than Daniel — no secret is hidden from you&#8221; — the ironic comparison to Daniel, the living standard of wisdom in Ezekiel's time (also in Ezek 14:14, 20). The prince of Tyre claims a wisdom that surpasses even the wisest of humans. Paul's response to this claim, applied to Christ: &#8220;in whom are hidden all the treasures of wisdom and knowledge&#8221; (Col 2:3). What the prince of Tyre claimed falsely — wisdom that surpasses Daniel, all secrets known — Christ possesses truly. The one who knew the secrets of every person's heart (John 2:24-25: &#8220;he knew all people ... he himself knew what was in man&#8221;) is the true answer to the wisdom-claim.</p>",
    "4": "<p>&#8220;By your wisdom and understanding you have gained wealth&#8221; — Tyre's wisdom produced commercial prosperity, paralleling Solomon's wisdom that produced material wealth (1 Kings 3:12-13: &#8220;I give you a wise and discerning heart ... I also give you what you have not asked, both riches and honor&#8221;). But Tyre's wisdom is self-attributing: it is credited to the prince's own intelligence, not to YHWH's gift. Proverbs 8 personifies Wisdom as the one through whom kings reign and wealth is found (Prov 8:15-21); Christ is &#8220;the wisdom of God&#8221; (1 Cor 1:24) in whom this figure is embodied. True wisdom produces true wealth (Prov 8:18) — Christ's riches are &#8220;unsearchable&#8221; (Eph 3:8).</p>",
    "5": "<p>&#8220;Your heart has become proud because of your wealth&#8221; — the sequence wisdom → wealth → pride is the diagnostic pattern. Deut 8:17-18 warns Israel against exactly this: &#8220;beware lest you say in your heart, 'My power and the might of my hand have gotten me this wealth.' You shall remember the LORD your God, for it is he who gives you power to get wealth.&#8221; Christ addresses the same pride in the parable of the rich fool (Luke 12:16-21) and warns: &#8220;a person's life does not consist in the abundance of his possessions&#8221; (Luke 12:15). The wealth that becomes pride is the seed of the judgment that follows in vv.6-10.</p>",
    "6": "<p>&#8220;Because you have set your heart as the heart of a god&#8221; — the therefore-of-judgment follows the because-of-sin. The structural logic of covenant lawsuit: accusation (vv.2-5) → verdict (v.6) → sentence (vv.7-10). Christ absorbs this lawsuit structure in his own passion: he is accused (John 19:7), sentenced (John 19:15-16), and executed — but the sentence he receives is not for his own pride but for ours. The covenant-lawsuit that the proud deserve falls on the innocent one, reversing the expected outcome.</p>",
    "7": "<p>&#8220;I will bring strangers against you, the most ruthless of the nations; they will draw their swords against the beauty of your wisdom and defile your splendor&#8221; — Babylon against Tyre's wisdom. What looks like military invasion is the divine deconstruction of false wisdom. Paul uses similar language for the cross: &#8220;God chose what is foolish in the world to shame the wise; God chose what is weak in the world to shame the strong&#8221; (1 Cor 1:27). The &#8220;ruthless nations&#8221; that YHWH brings against proud wisdom are a type of the divine folly of the cross that defeats human wisdom more effectively than any army.</p>",
    "8": "<p>&#8220;They will thrust you down into the Pit, and you will die the death of the slain in the heart of the seas&#8221; — the Pit (<em>shachat</em>) is Sheol, the place of the dead. The prince who claimed to sit in the seat of gods is thrust into the lowest place. This is the precise reversal of the Magnificat pattern: &#8220;he has brought down the mighty from their thrones and exalted those of humble estate&#8221; (Luke 1:52). Christ himself enters the Pit — &#8220;you will not abandon my soul to Hades&#8221; (Acts 2:27, Ps 16:10) — but rises from it, unlike the prince of Tyre whose descent is permanent.</p>",
    "9": "<p>&#8220;Will you still say, 'I am a god,' before the one who kills you? But you will be a mere man in the hand of the one who wounds you&#8221; — the death-chamber revelation: divinity claims dissolve before the sword. This is the prophetic demythologization of human pretension: in the moment of death, all claims to divine status are exposed as lies. Christ's death on the cross appeared to be the same demythologization of his divine claims (Mark 15:29-32: &#8220;let him come down from the cross and we will believe him&#8221;). But the resurrection is YHWH's counter-verdict: what looked like the exposure of Christ's messianic claim as false was the vindication of that claim in the most definitive possible way.</p>",
    "10": "<p>&#8220;You will die the death of the uncircumcised by the hand of foreigners&#8221; — the maximum shame of the Ezekielian Sheol-gallery (see ch.32). The prince who claimed divine status will die in the company of the uncircumcised — those without covenant identity. This is the judgment that falls on all who claim divine status without possessing it. Christ, who is truly divine, willingly accepted the shameful death of a criminal (crucifixion was the death of slaves and rebels, not of citizens and the covenanted) — absorbing the shame that should fall on those who falsely claim divine status, so that those who genuinely belong to him are covered by his righteousness.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The second word-of-the-LORD formula introduces the king-oracle (vv.11-19) with a higher register than the prince-oracle. The shift from &#8220;prince&#8221; to &#8220;king&#8221; signals a different level of discourse: the king-oracle will exceed what can be said of any merely human ruler. The dual oracle structure (prince → king) mirrors other prophetic dual-level oracles (Isa 14:4-21 speaks both of the king of Babylon and, many interpreters argue, of a transcendent figure behind him; Dan 10:13, 20-21 speaks of the spiritual &#8220;prince&#8221; of Persia and Greece behind the earthly kings).</p>",
    "12": "<p>&#8220;You were the seal of perfection, full of wisdom and perfect in beauty&#8221; — these attributes cannot apply to any historical king of Tyre: no human ruler has ever been &#8220;the seal of perfection&#8221; (<em>totem tachlit</em>). The figure described is one who began in a state of genuine, complete perfection — wisdom without limit, beauty without flaw. The only being to whom this can be said truthfully is Christ: &#8220;the radiance of the glory of God and the exact imprint of his nature&#8221; (Heb 1:3); &#8220;the image of the invisible God&#8221; (Col 1:15). What the king of Tyre's ode describes as a state now lost, Christ embodies as a permanent identity.</p>",
    "13": "<p>&#8220;You were in Eden, the garden of God&#8221; — the placement of this figure in Eden, the primordial divine garden, exceeds any historical king. The gemstones listed (ruby, topaz, crystal, beryl, onyx, jasper, lapis lazuli, turquoise, emerald) are nearly identical to those on the high priest's breastplate (Exod 28:17-20), suggesting this figure was adorned as a priestly guardian of the divine presence. &#8220;The craftsmanship of your settings and engravings was prepared in you on the day you were created&#8221; — a created being, but created for the highest possible role. Many interpreters (from Origen to modern scholars) read this as describing the being behind the king of Tyre: a guardian cherub who had access to Eden but fell. Christologically, Christ is the one who restores Eden-access (Rev 2:7: &#8220;to the one who conquers I will grant to eat of the tree of life, which is in the paradise of God&#8221;).</p>",
    "14": "<p>&#8220;You were the anointed guardian cherub; I had appointed you. You were on the holy mountain of God; you walked among the stones of fire&#8221; — the cherub (<em>kerub</em>) was the specific category of heavenly being that guarded sacred space: the cherubim on the ark (Exod 25:18-22), the cherubim in the Holy of Holies (1 Kings 6:23-28), the cherubim that drove Adam and Eve from Eden (Gen 3:24). &#8220;Anointed&#8221; (<em>mimshach</em>) — the same root as Messiah (<em>mashiach</em>). The anointed guardian cherub was set apart for the highest function: protecting the divine presence. Christ is the anointed one (Ps 2:2; Acts 4:26-27) who also guards and gives access to the divine presence — not by excluding sinners from the throne but by opening the way for them through his blood (Heb 10:19-22).</p>",
    "15": "<p>&#8220;You were blameless in your ways from the day you were created until iniquity was found in you&#8221; — the blamelessness that characterized this being from creation is the perfection Christ alone permanently retains. Jesus was &#8220;without sin&#8221; (Heb 4:15), &#8220;holy, innocent, unstained, separated from sinners&#8221; (Heb 7:26), &#8220;a lamb without blemish or spot&#8221; (1 Pet 1:19). The &#8220;until iniquity was found&#8221; applies to the figure in the oracle, not to Christ — but the contrast is precisely the Christological point: where the guardian cherub fell from blamelessness, Christ maintained it through the full course of his life, qualifying him to be the sufficient sacrifice.</p>",
    "16": "<p>&#8220;Through the abundance of your trade you were filled inwardly with violence, and you sinned; so I cast you out as profane from the mountain of God&#8221; — the fall: inward violence, sin, expulsion from the holy mountain. Luke 10:18: &#8220;I saw Satan fall like lightning from heaven&#8221; — Jesus's reference to a primordial expulsion from the divine mountain is the NT's closest parallel to this verse. The casting out of the guardian cherub from the mountain of God is what Christ came to undo: he entered the territory of the fallen guardian (the world, which John describes as lying in the power of the evil one, 1 John 5:19) and defeated him (John 12:31; Rev 20:10).</p>",
    "17": "<p>&#8220;Your heart was proud because of your beauty; you corrupted your wisdom for the sake of your splendor. I have cast you to the ground and exposed you before kings&#8221; — the pride of beauty corrupting wisdom is the original pattern of spiritual fall: the created glory becoming the occasion for self-exaltation rather than YHWH-glorification. Christ is the one who &#8220;came to serve and not to be served&#8221; (Mark 10:45) and whose beauty was hidden in humiliation (Isa 53:2: &#8220;he had no form or majesty that we should look at him, and no beauty that we should desire him&#8221;). The one whose eternal beauty was uncorrupted by pride was exposed before kings — not in shame, but in the definitive act of divine love.</p>",
    "18": "<p>&#8220;By the abundance of your iniquities ... you defiled your sanctuaries; therefore I brought out fire from your midst — it consumed you, and I turned you to ashes on the earth&#8221; — fire from within consuming the sinful figure. This is the self-consuming nature of sin: the fire of judgment begins from the inside, not the outside. Christ absorbed this fire at Golgotha — &#8220;our God is a consuming fire&#8221; (Heb 12:29) and Christ bore the divine fire on behalf of sinners, so that those who are united to him are not consumed. The ashes on the earth where Tyre's glory stood become the ashes of repentance from which resurrection rises.</p>",
    "19": "<p>&#8220;All who knew you among the peoples are appalled at you; you have become a horror and shall be no more forever&#8221; — the permanent end of the one who fell from perfection. This permanent end is the theological statement about the irreversibility of the fall from the guardian cherub's original estate — unlike human sinners for whom restoration is possible (and for whom Christ came), the figure behind the king of Tyre oracle has passed the point of no return. Revelation 20:10 confirms this: the devil &#8220;will be tormented day and night forever and ever.&#8221; Christ's redemption is for the human beings who were deceived by the fallen cherub, not for the cherub itself — this is the scope and limit of the atonement's application.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The third word-of-the-LORD formula introduces the brief Sidon oracle (vv.21-23). Sidon, Tyre's northern neighbor, is addressed in a shorter oracle without the extended lament of the Tyre oracles. The structure of chs.25-28 systematically covers the nations surrounding Israel: Ammon, Moab, Edom, Philistia (ch.25), Tyre (chs.26-28), and Sidon (28:20-23). Christ's gospel eventually reaches all these nations (Rom 15:16-19: &#8220;from Jerusalem and all the way around to Illyricum I have fulfilled the ministry of the gospel of Christ&#8221;; Acts 27:3 mentions Sidon as one of Paul's ports of call).</p>",
    "21": "<p>&#8220;Son of man, set your face against Sidon and prophesy against it&#8221; — the confrontation formula applied to Sidon. Sidon was the northern Phoenician city-state, older than Tyre and historically important in the patriarchal period (Gen 10:15: Sidon is Canaan's firstborn son). Jesus himself traveled to the region of Tyre and Sidon and healed a Canaanite/Syrophoenician woman (Matt 15:21-28; Mark 7:24-30) — the judgment-oracle over Sidon becomes the location of a healing that Jesus uses to expand his mission beyond Israel. The judgments of the OT become the opportunities of the NT.</p>",
    "22": "<p>&#8220;I will be glorified in your midst ... I will display my holiness in her&#8221; — YHWH's holiness is displayed through judgment: &#8220;I am holy in those who are near me, and before all the people I will be glorified&#8221; (Lev 10:3, after Nadab and Abihu's death). Christ is &#8220;the Holy One of God&#8221; (Mark 1:24; John 6:69) whose holiness is displayed not through punitive destruction but through the cross, where divine holiness and divine love meet in perfect unity. Sidon witnesses YHWH's glory; the whole world witnesses Christ's glory in the cross and resurrection (John 12:23-24: &#8220;the hour has come for the Son of Man to be glorified ... unless a grain of wheat falls into the earth and dies&#8221;).</p>",
    "23": "<p>&#8220;The slain will fall in her midst by the sword that comes against her from every side — and they will know that I am the LORD&#8221; — the knowledge formula after judgment. The historical fulfillment came through Babylonian, Persian, and Seleucid conquests of Sidon (Sidon was razed by Artaxerxes III in 345 BCE). The &#8220;they will know&#8221; formula finds its deepest fulfillment in the crucifixion narrative: the Roman centurion who witnessed the manner of Christ's death said &#8220;truly this man was the Son of God&#8221; (Mark 15:39) — the knowledge of YHWH's identity coming through the death of the one who bears his name.</p>",
    "24": "<p>&#8220;There will no longer be a painful brier or a piercing thorn from any of the surrounding peoples who showed contempt for Israel&#8221; — the removal of briers and thorns. The thorn-brier imagery goes back to the curse of Genesis 3:18: &#8220;thorns and thistles it shall bring forth for you.&#8221; The surrounding nations are described as thorns in Israel's side (Num 33:55; Josh 23:13). Christ wore a crown of thorns at the crucifixion (Matt 27:29; John 19:2) — visually absorbing the curse of the thorns, taking onto himself the &#8220;brier&#8221; that the nations represent, so that &#8220;there will no longer be a painful brier.&#8221; The removal of the thorn-nations in Ezekiel's oracle is accomplished Christologically through Christ's absorption of the curse.</p>",
    "25": "<p>&#8220;When I gather the house of Israel from the peoples among whom they have been scattered, and display my holiness in them before the eyes of the nations, then they will dwell in their own land that I gave to my servant Jacob&#8221; — the restoration promise after the judgment oracles. The gathering of scattered Israel is the eschatological gathering that the NT applies to Christ: &#8220;he died ... to gather into one the children of God who are scattered abroad&#8221; (John 11:52). The Jacob-land promise is fulfilled in the new creation where &#8220;the meek shall inherit the earth&#8221; (Matt 5:5; cf. Ps 37:11) — the land given to Jacob's offspring becomes, in Christ, the renewed earth given to all who are Abraham's children by faith.</p>",
    "26": "<p>&#8220;They will dwell in it safely and build houses and plant vineyards. They will live with confidence when I have executed judgments against all their surrounding neighbors who showed them contempt. And they will know that I am the LORD their God&#8221; — the concluding restoration promise. Safety, houses, vineyards, confidence — the covenant blessing formula from Lev 26:5 (&#8220;you shall live in your land securely&#8221;) and Mic 4:4 (&#8220;every man shall sit under his vine and under his fig tree&#8221;). Christ is the &#8220;prince of peace&#8221; (Isa 9:6) through whom this security is established — not by military elimination of the nations but by their conversion through the gospel (Rev 21:24: &#8220;by its light will the nations walk&#8221;). The knowledge formula that closes the oracle — &#8220;they will know that I am the LORD their God&#8221; — is the full covenant-restoration formula: not merely knowledge of YHWH's power but relational knowledge of YHWH as their God, achieved through Christ's reconciling work.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'ezekiel')
    merge_comm(existing, EZEKIEL_CHRIST)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', 'ezekiel', existing)
    for ch in ['26', '27', '28']:
        vv = existing.get(ch, {})
        print(f'  ch{ch}: {len(vv)} verse(s) with christ commentary')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
